resourceInfo.abstract:
We will develop an approach to identify fire refugia in Rocky Mountain ecosystems of the U.S. and Canada then test the function of refugia for biodiversity conservation under current and future climate/fire scenarios. Our products will be designed to inform decision-making in land/easement acquisition, identification of critical areas for maintaining landscape and process connectivity/permeability, and extension of the temporal context for spatial conservation decision making. The approach will be testable for transferability to other locations and ecosystems.

FY2013
Objectives:
 
The proposed project will provide a science application for focused resource conservation by developing and testing the concept of refugia in the fire-adapted ecosystems of the Rocky Mountains of the northern US and Canada. In the process, we will test assumptions of model predictions (for example, are physical refugia functioning as biodiversity refugia) and inventory resource conditions, including quantification of spatial patterns of refugial habitats. The ability to spatially and temporally predict the location of potential refugia on the landscape under current and future climate scenarios will allow managers to identify places that may warrant specific consideration in conservation planning. Wilderness ecosystems in the study areas provide a valuable learning environment where confounding effects of resource management (e.g., logging and roads) are minimized. Although we look at two forested study regions, the predictive models will be based on physical variables and therefore should be applicable to other landscapes, such as sagebrush-steppe, which have parallel issues. 

Specifically, we will:
 Model potential locations of refugia by examining the fundamental link between the observed fire-refugia and the environment in which they were generated
 Describe species and habitats protected in potential refugia using remote sensing and field data
